Class BramsprCompiler

  • java.lang.Object
    • org.antlr.v4.runtime.tree.AbstractParseTreeVisitor<T>
      • bramspr.BramsprBaseVisitor<Symbol>
        • bramspr.BramsprCompiler
  • All Implemented Interfaces:
    BramsprVisitor<Symbol>, org.antlr.v4.runtime.tree.ParseTreeVisitor<Symbol>, org.objectweb.asm.Opcodes

    public class BramsprCompiler
extends BramsprBaseVisitor<Symbol>
implements org.objectweb.asm.Opcodes
    This class is responsible for the actual compilation of Bramspr programs. Intended to be used in conjunction with BramsprLexer, BramsprParser and BramsprChecker. The code generation starts with feeding a parse tree + parse tree decoration as generated by BramsprParser and BramsprChecker to compile(org.antlr.v4.runtime.tree.ParseTree, org.antlr.v4.runtime.tree.ParseTreeProperty<bramspr.symboltable.Symbol>, java.lang.String). The program then gets translated to Java bytecode by recursive calls to various visit-methods this class contains.

      • mainFileName

        private java.lang.String mainFileName
        The name of the main class this code will compile to, e.g. "Bramspr" or "Math"

      • inReadAccessToField

        private boolean inReadAccessToField
        Whether the compiler is in a "read" state, or in a "write" state.
        If it's in a write state, field access should put a reference on the stack.
        If it's in read access, the value of the field should be put on the stack.

      • closingScopeLabels

        private java.util.Stack<org.objectweb.asm.Label> closingScopeLabels
        Contains the last label of every scope we have visited. Grows one every time a scope is opened. These labels are used in the elements of variables to mark the end of their scope.

      • variables

        private java.util.ArrayList<VariableSymbol> variables
        Maintains a list of the variables we have visited. Stores name, type, opening_label, closing_label (excl.) This allows us to do a massive mv.visitLocalVariable(...) iteration at the end of the class, to declare the variables.

      • claimMemAddr

        private int claimMemAddr(VariableSymbol variable)
        To be called when visiting a variableDeclaration (also the implicit ones: the parameters in a functioncall). Sets the memory address of the parameter, increases the counter and makes sure that the scope of visibility is taken care of.
        Parameters:
        variable - the newly declared variable that needs a place in our memory
        Returns:
        the memory address assigned to the variable

      • closeScope

        private void closeScope()
        Closes a scope by popping and writing a scope from the closingScopeLabels stack to assembly. This ensures variables are not visible too long.

      • dumpAssembly

        public void dumpAssembly()
        Prints a (somewhat) human-readable dump of the assembly to the standard output.

      • compile

        public java.util.ArrayList<BramsprCompiler.BramsprClass> compile(org.antlr.v4.runtime.tree.ParseTree tree,
                                                        org.antlr.v4.runtime.tree.ParseTreeProperty<Symbol> ptp,
                                                        java.lang.String className)
        Generates bytecode for the JVM from a parsetree. The generated bytecode contains a main class that semantically matches the bramspr sourcecode that produced the parsetree and parsetreeproperty.
        Parameters:
        tree - the parsetree generated from the sourcecode
        ptp - a map from Contexts to Symbols, containing the information needed to link variables, functions, types and enums to their declaration.
        className - the name of the file, which corresponds to the name of the class.
        Returns:
        Java bytecode array that can be written to a file and executed by calling java className

      • visitMultipleComparisonExpression

        private void visitMultipleComparisonExpression(int comparisonOpCode,
                                     BramsprParser.ArithmeticContext[] arithmeticContexts)
        Generates a lazy evaluation comparison between two or more integers. Possible comparators are: <, <=, =, =/=, >= and >. Upon the first false value, the expression yields false. This function is used by the integer comparators.

        public Symbol visitFunctionCall(BramsprParser.FunctionCallContext ctx)

      • visitPotentialEnumerationLiteral

        public Symbol visitPotentialEnumerationLiteral(BramsprParser.PotentialEnumerationLiteralContext ctx)
        Visits a possible enumeration; this is either an fieldaccess or an enumeration. If it is an enumeration, this function puts one int value on the stack. If it is a field access, the value of the field is put on the stack (since a potentialEnumerationLiteral is always read access, never write access).

      • isJBCPrimitive

        private boolean isJBCPrimitive(TypeSymbol type)
        Tests whether a type is a JBC primitive. The JBC primitives are (as far as we're concerned) integer, boolean, character and enumerations. Note that doubles etc. are not part of our language. These "primitives" are all stored as int values, and can be handled with the I functions, e.g. ISTORE, IADD, etc.
        Parameters:
        type - the type to be checked
        Returns:
        true iff type is an enum, integer, character or boolean
